<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO JJ THE BOONIRAT</font><br>
<tt>Sun Feb  9 16:41:16 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To JJ the Boonirat,<br><br>
I understand your perspective, and in fact, one could conclude things such as you have done.<br><br>
You said:<br><br>
&quot;This is my first time to see this site. Therefore,<br>
I have no feel for what this is really all about. I<br>
admit that up front. My first impression is that <br>
somehow a small group of people are enjoying some<br>
kind of intellectual game about Nam, Protestors, the<br>
Vets, and a series of overlapping generations.&quot;<br><br>
I would like to express my feelings about your perception of an intellectual game so that you might better understand the process that is at work here for me.<br><br>
I suffer from PTSD, as do many Vietnam Veterans. I have discovered in the past year that I have been fighting the war at many levels in my mind for the past 26 years. This has not been at all good, and, in fact, it has been very destructive. The flashbacks, anger, rage, dissociation, and other things are the result. In retrospect, the impact upon my family has been awful. I just didn't know any better.<br><br>
My exploration with protestors is a portion of a larger process at work with me. I use the word exploration very explicitly. This is not a game with me, but some very risky and very important business. <br><br>
I am extending myself &quot;out there&quot; to learn if it is OK to stop fighting now.
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


